    clinicalExplanation: "Hemodynamic monitoring provides real-time data about cardiovascular performance including heart rate, blood pressure, cardiac output, vascular resistance, and filling pressures. Invasive monitoring through arterial lines, central venous catheters, and pulmonary artery catheters allows precise measurement of parameters that non-invasive methods cannot capture. Understanding the determinants of cardiac output (heart rate × stroke volume) and the factors affecting stroke volume (preload, afterload, contractility) is fundamental to interpreting hemodynamic data and titrating interventions.",
    nursingInterventions: [
      { title: "Arterial Line Management", description: "Zero and level the transducer at the phlebostatic axis (4th ICS, mid-axillary line) every shift and with position changes. Maintain continuous flush at 300 mmHg. Monitor waveform quality — identify overdamped and underdamped waveforms. Assess insertion site for signs of infection. Check distal circulation (Allen test).", priority: "high" },
      { title: "CVP Monitoring and Interpretation", description: "Monitor central venous pressure trends rather than single values (normal 2-8 mmHg). Low CVP may indicate hypovolemia; elevated CVP may suggest right heart failure, fluid overload, or cardiac tamponade. Correlate CVP with clinical assessment and fluid responsiveness testing.", priority: "high" },
      { title: "Cardiac Output Interpretation", description: "Monitor cardiac output (normal 4-8 L/min) and cardiac index (normal 2.5-4.0 L/min/m²). Calculate systemic vascular resistance (normal 800-1200 dynes/sec/cm⁻⁵). Use hemodynamic profiles to differentiate shock types and guide vasopressor, inotrope, and fluid therapy.", priority: "high" },
      { title: "Waveform Analysis", description: "Interpret arterial, CVP, and PA waveforms for accuracy and clinical significance. Recognize artifacts vs. true clinical changes. Identify dampened waveforms and troubleshoot causes. Correlate waveform changes with patient status changes.", priority: "medium" },
      { title: "Infection Prevention", description: "Maintain sterile dressing over insertion sites. Perform daily site assessment using standardized tools. Follow CLABSI prevention bundle. Minimize line entries. Use sterile technique for blood draws from arterial lines.", priority: "medium" },
    ],
    medications: [
      { drugClass: "Vasopressors", examples: "Norepinephrine, vasopressin, phenylephrine, epinephrine", nursingConsiderations: "Titrate based on hemodynamic targets (MAP, SVR, CO); central line required; continuous monitoring; assess for end-organ perfusion" },
      { drugClass: "Inotropes", examples: "Dobutamine, milrinone, dopamine", nursingConsiderations: "Increase cardiac contractility; dobutamine may cause hypotension; milrinone — loading dose caution; monitor heart rate and arrhythmias" },
      { drugClass: "Vasodilators", examples: "Nitroglycerin, nitroprusside, nicardipine", nursingConsiderations: "Reduce afterload/preload; protect from light (nitroprusside); monitor for cyanide toxicity (nitroprusside); continuous BP monitoring required" },
      { drugClass: "Heparin Flush", examples: "Heparinized saline (if used per facility protocol)", nursingConsiderations: "Many facilities use non-heparinized NS flush; maintain continuous flush pressure at 300 mmHg; monitor for HIT if heparin used" },
    ],
    previewQuestionsSlugs: ["cardiovascular", "critical-care", "icu"],
    relatedLessonSlugs: ["hemodynamic-monitoring", "cardiovascular-assessment", "shock-management"],
    relatedFlashcardSlugs: ["cardiovascular-system", "critical-care-medications", "lab-values"],
    relatedTopicSlugs: ["sepsis-nursing-interventions", "ventilator-management-nursing", "cardiac-rhythm-interpretation-nursing"],
    faqs: [
      { question: "What is the phlebostatic axis and why is leveling important?", answer: "The phlebostatic axis is located at the 4th intercostal space at the mid-axillary line, corresponding to the level of the right atrium. Leveling the transducer to this point ensures accurate pressure measurements. A transducer positioned too high reads falsely low; positioned too low reads falsely high. Releveling is required with any patient position change." },
      { question: "How do nurses differentiate shock types using hemodynamic data?", answer: "Cardiogenic shock: low CO, high SVR, high CVP/PCWP. Hypovolemic shock: low CO, high SVR, low CVP/PCWP. Distributive/septic shock: initially high CO, low SVR, variable CVP. Obstructive shock: low CO, high SVR, elevated CVP. Understanding these profiles guides appropriate vasopressor, fluid, and inotrope selection." },
      { question: "What is a dampened arterial waveform and how should nurses troubleshoot it?", answer: "A dampened waveform shows a blunted peak with loss of dicrotic notch, indicating a falsely low systolic and falsely high diastolic reading. Causes include air bubbles in tubing, blood clot, kinking, loose connections, or catheter position against the vessel wall. Troubleshoot by flushing the line, checking connections, repositioning the wrist, and ensuring adequate flush bag pressure." },
      { question: "What is the normal range for pulmonary artery wedge pressure (PCWP)?", answer: "Normal PCWP (pulmonary capillary wedge pressure) is 6-12 mmHg. Elevated PCWP (>18 mmHg) suggests left heart failure or fluid overload. Low PCWP (<6 mmHg) suggests hypovolemia. PCWP reflects left atrial pressure and is used to assess left ventricular preload and guide fluid therapy." },
    ],
