    color: "#2563EB",
    colorAccent: "#DBEAFE",
    introduction: "Preparing for the NCLEX requires more than memorizing facts. It demands the ability to apply clinical knowledge to patient scenarios, prioritize nursing actions, and demonstrate sound clinical judgment. A well-structured question bank is the single most effective study tool for NCLEX preparation. Research consistently shows that students who complete 2,000-3,000 practice questions with thorough rationale review have the highest first-attempt pass rates. This comprehensive guide covers everything you need to know about using a question bank effectively and developing the critical thinking skills that separate passing candidates from those who need to retake the exam.",
    clinicalExplanation: "The NCLEX uses Computerized Adaptive Testing (CAT) technology that adjusts question difficulty based on your performance. The Next Generation NCLEX (NGN) introduced new question types that test clinical judgment using the NCSBN Clinical Judgment Measurement Model (CJMM). This model includes six cognitive processes: Recognize Cues (identifying relevant assessment data), Analyze Cues (linking data to patient conditions), Prioritize Hypotheses (ranking potential problems), Generate Solutions (identifying appropriate interventions), Take Action (implementing the best intervention), and Evaluate Outcomes (assessing intervention effectiveness). NGN question types include Extended Multiple Response with partial credit, Extended Drag-and-Drop, Matrix/Grid questions, Enhanced Hot Spot, Cloze drop-down completion, and Unfolding Case Studies. Effective question bank use involves three strategies: content-mode studying by topic, random-mode practice across all topics, and timed practice exams simulating real testing conditions.",
    nursingInterventions: [
      { title: "Daily Practice Question Routine", description: "Complete 75-150 practice questions per day in the final 2-4 weeks before the exam. Start with content-focused blocks, then transition to random 75-question sets. Review every rationale, correct or incorrect.", priority: "high" },
      { title: "Rationale-Based Learning", description: "After each question, read the complete rationale for every option. Understanding why wrong answers are wrong is as valuable as knowing the right answer. Create flashcards for concepts you miss repeatedly.", priority: "high" },
      { title: "Weakness Identification", description: "Track your performance by content area. Focus additional study time on areas where your accuracy is below 60%. Use analytics to identify patterns in your mistakes.", priority: "high" },
      { title: "Clinical Judgment Practice", description: "Prioritize NGN-style questions including unfolding case studies. Practice the CJMM framework: identify relevant cues, analyze them, determine the priority problem, and select the best intervention.", priority: "high" },
      { title: "Test-Taking Strategy Development", description: "Learn systematic approaches: ABC prioritization, Maslow hierarchy, nursing process steps, and assessment before intervention. Practice eliminating distractors.", priority: "medium" },
    ],
    medications: [
      { drugClass: "High-Yield NCLEX Medications", examples: "Digoxin, warfarin, heparin, insulin, potassium chloride, magnesium sulfate", nursingConsiderations: "Know therapeutic levels, key assessments before administration, antidotes, and patient education for each" },
      { drugClass: "Emergency Medications", examples: "Epinephrine, atropine, amiodarone, naloxone, flumazenil, adenosine", nursingConsiderations: "Know indications, doses, routes, and expected outcomes; frequently tested in prioritization questions" },
      { drugClass: "Common Antidotes", examples: "Naloxone (opioids), flumazenil (benzos), protamine (heparin), vitamin K (warfarin)", nursingConsiderations: "Match each antidote to its toxicity; know onset of action and monitoring requirements" },
    ],
